Title: Haydn Symphony No. 102 (Beecham, 1949)
Description:
Haydn: Symphony No. 102 in B-Flat Major
Royal Philharmonic Orchestra, conducted by Sir Thomas Beecham (1949)
Originally posted Dec. 22, 2008

Recorded on June 11, June 23, and October 1, 1949, in EMI's Studio No. 1, Abbey Road, London, on Gramophone Company matrices 2EA 13975 through 13980.  Issued as HMV DB 21042 through DB 21044, and in automatic sequence as DB 9449 through DB 9451.  These are the only forms of issue of which I am aware, and, as a result, this remains perhaps the least-known of all Beecham's Haydn recordings.

Haydn's Symphony No. 102 is in four movements:

1. Largo; Allegro vivace (at 2:30)
2. Adagio (at 7:48)
3. Menuetto: Allegro (at 13:26)
4. Presto (at 19:13)

Title: SIBELIUS - Symphony No. 2, Op. 43 ~ BBC Symphony Orchestra, Thomas Beecham (Live recording 1954)
Description:
Silbelius: Symphony No. 2 in D major, Op. 43
BBC Symphony Orchestra
Thomas Beecham
Live recording at Royal Festival Hall, London, 8 December 1954
00:00 - Allegretto
08:49 - Tempo Andante, ma rubato
21:02 - Vivacissimo
27:31 - Finale. Allegro moderato
A composição da Sinfonia nº 2 em ré maior, Op. 43, foi iniciada no inverno de 1901 em Rapallo, Itália, logo após a estreia bem-sucedida do popular “Finlandia”, e concluída em 1902 na Finlândia. Sibelius disse: "Minha segunda sinfonia é uma confissão da alma." O barão Axel Carpelan, que deu o nome ao conhecido poema sinfônico de Sibelius, “Finlandia”, escreveu ao compositor logo após sua estreia de sucesso: "Você está preso em casa há um bom tempo, é hora de você viajar. Você passará o final do outono e o inverno na Itália, um país onde se aprende o “cantábile”, equilíbrio e harmonia, plasticidade e simetria das linhas, um país onde tudo é belo – até o feio é belo na Itália”. Embora o Barão Carpelan não tivesse dinheiro para financiar essa viagem, ele levantou fundos suficientes para Sibelius ficar em uma vila nas montanhas perto de Rapallo, Itália, onde o compositor anotou as primeiras notas da sinfonia.

Title: Sir Thomas Beecham and London Philharmonic Orchestra - Symphony No.99 in E flat (Haydn) (1935/6)
Description:
Sir Thomas Beecham conducts the LPO in Haydn's Symphony No. 99, recorded on 4 October 1935 (except for the first part of the second movement, which was recorded on 28 February 1936).

The movements are:

00:00 1st movement
07:21 2nd movement
13:39 3rd movement
18:55 4th movement

From Wikipedia: Sir Thomas Beecham, 2nd Baronet, CH (29 April 1879 – 8 March 1961) was an English conductor and impresario best known for his association with the London Philharmonic and the Royal Philharmonic orchestras. He was also closely associated with the Liverpool Philharmonic and Hallé orchestras. From the early 20th century until his death, Beecham was a major influence on the musical life of Britain and, according to the BBC, was Britain's first international conductor.

Born to a rich industrial family, Beecham began his career as a conductor in 1899. He used his access to the family fortune to finance opera from the 1910s until the start of the Second World War, staging seasons at Covent Garden, Drury Lane and His Majesty's Theatre with international stars, his own orchestra and a wide repertoire. Among the works he introduced to England were Richard Strauss's Elektra, Salome and Der Rosenkavalier and three operas by Frederick Delius.

Together with his younger colleague Malcolm Sargent, Beecham founded the London Philharmonic, and he conducted its first performance at the Queen's Hall in 1932. In the 1940s he worked for three years in the United States where he was music director of the Seattle Symphony and conducted at the Metropolitan Opera. After his return to Britain, he founded the Royal Philharmonic in 1946 and conducted it until his death in 1961.

Beecham's repertoire was eclectic, sometimes favouring lesser-known composers over famous ones. His specialities included composers whose works were neglected in Britain before he became their advocate, such as Delius and Berlioz. Other composers with whose music he was frequently associated were Haydn, Schubert, Sibelius and the composer he revered above all others, Mozart.


I made this transfer from Australian laminated 78 rpm pressings of LOX 305/7.

Title: Sir Thomas Beecham/London Philharmonic Orchestra - Symphony No.93 in D major 'London' (Haydn) (1936)

Title: Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart -  Symphony No. 40 - Sir Thomas Beecham
Description:
Music By Freemasons

Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart was admitted to the Viennese Masonic lodge “Zur Wohltatigkeit” (“Benificence”) on Tuesday, 14th December, 1784. Mozart apparently introduced his father, Leopold Mozart, and his friend Franz Joseph Haydn into Freemasonry. 

Mozart's last three symphonies, No. 39, 40, 41, are considered Masonic symphonies because of the key they are in. Here is a web page from the Temple Lodge No. 33 website with further information on this and on Mozart And Freemasonry:  http://www.templelodge33.ca/wolfgang-amadeus-mozart-and-freemasonry/  

This recording of Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart's  Symphony No. 40 In G Minor, K, 550 by Sir Thomas Beecham (1879-1961) conducting the Royal Philharmonic Orchestra was released by Columbia Records on its Odyssey Records subsidiary.

Track list:

1. Allegro Molto     0.00
2. Andante               5:27​
3. Menuetto, Allegretto      14:31​
4. Finale, Allegro                19:38​

The recording is in mono and the audio was taken from a US pressing of the Odyssey Records vinyl LP, part of a 3 record set of Mozart's last six symphonies.

I have uploaded separate videos of each of the six Mozart symphonies in this Odyssey Records collection.  

[Note: as far as I am aware, this recording is not currently available commercially]
